## Inline, Internal, and External CSS

### Inline CSS
* **Definition:** CSS rules are defined within the HTML element itself, using the `style` attribute.
* **Example:**
  ```html
  <h1 style="color: red; font-size: 36px;">Hello, World!</h1>
  ```
* **Advantages:**
  - Quick and easy to implement for one-off styling changes.
* **Disadvantages:**
  - Poor maintainability: Styles are hard to manage and reuse across multiple elements.
  - Separation of concerns is violated, making the HTML code less readable and maintainable.

### Internal CSS
* **Definition:** CSS rules are defined within the `<head>` section of an HTML document using the `<style>` tag.
* **Example:**
  ```html
  <!DOCTYPE html>
  <html>
  <head>
      <title>Internal CSS</title>
      <style>
          h1 {
              color: blue;
              font-size: 24px;
          }
      </style>
  </head>
  <body>
      <h1>Hello, World!</h1>
  </body>
  </html>
  ```
* **Advantages:**
  - Improves maintainability compared to inline CSS.
  - Styles can be reused within the same HTML document.
* **Disadvantages:**
  - Not suitable for large-scale projects or sharing styles across multiple pages.
  - Still violates separation of concerns to some extent.

### External CSS
* **Definition:** CSS rules are defined in a separate `.css` file and linked to the HTML document using the `<link>` tag.
* **Example:**
  ```html
  <!DOCTYPE html>
  <html>
  <head>
      <title>External CSS</title>
      <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">
  </head>
  <body>
      <h1>Hello, World!</h1>
  </body>
  </html>
  ```
  **styles.css:**
  ```css
  h1 {
      color: green;
      font-size: 20px;
  }
  ```
* **Advantages:**
  - Best practice for large-scale projects and maintaining separation of concerns.
  - Styles can be reused across multiple HTML pages.
  - Improves code organization and readability.
* **Disadvantages:**
  - Requires an additional HTTP request to load the CSS file, potentially slowing down page load time (though modern browsers often cache CSS files).

### Demonstrating All Three Methods
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>CSS Methods</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">
    <style>
        h2 {
            color: purple;
            font-size: 28px;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1 style="color: red; font-size: 36px;">Inline CSS</h1>
    <h2>Internal CSS</h2>
    <h1>External CSS</h1>
</body>
</html>
```

**styles.css:**
```css
h1 {
    color: blue;
    font-size: 24px;
}
```

This example demonstrates all three CSS methods applied to the same HTML elements. You can observe the differences in styling and the impact of each method on the code structure.